<hl>
<seg id=1> The Bangkok Elevated Railroad Project Will Be Restarted </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP. Bankok) The Department of Transportation of Thailand yesterday announced that they would claim US$6.8 billion (approximately 11 billion Singapore dollars) from Hongkong listed Hopewell Corporation for their failing to accomplish the contract on time when building the Bankok elevated railroad and highway system. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Paradi, deputy minister of the Department of Transportation, said that the Department of Transportation and the National Railway Bureau have the right to claim US$6.8 billion from Hopewell Corporation for the loss of delaying the project, and Thailand reproached that in the past 8 years Hopewell Corporation had only finished 12% of the planned project. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> After the Thailand economic crisis, Hopewell Corporation negotiated with Thailand authorities on the aggravated financial disputes and the disputes on the progress of land requisition, which were caused by the devaluation of Thailand currency. The Thailand authorities had terminated the contract with Hopewell Corporation on January this year. </seg>
<seg id=5> For this reason, The Hopewell Corporation wanted to claim 100 billion bahts (approximately 4.2 billion Singapore dollars) from the Thailand government in order to compensate for the money invested in the past 8 years and for the part of the project that has been finished. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Thailand government said yesterday that Thailand was planning to restart this US$ 3.2 billion project, but considering narrowing down the project scale. </seg>
<seg id=7> But, at any rate, they would not allow Hopewell Corporation to participate in the project any more. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Paradi said that German Government and KFW are interested in revitalizing this huge project and have decided to offer 0.1 billion bahts for the feasibility research of the Bangkok elevated railway and highway system project. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Siemens Co. of Germany at present is cooperating with a local company in Thailand, carrying out a project of paving another 23-kilometer-long electronic railway. </seg>
</p>
